{"cursor":"72342","size":15,"audio":[],"cat":[],"tmpl":[],"currentlang":"en","linknr":582,"url":"Radar","article":"\n, known as ALTAIR, used to detect and track space objects in conjunction with\nABM testing at the Ronald Reagan Test Site on Kwajalein Atoll.]]\n. The antenna rotates at a steady rate, sweeping the local airspace with a\n  narrow vertical fan-shaped beam, to detect aircraft at all altitudes.]]\n\n'Radar' is an object detection system which uses radio waves to determine the\nrange, altitude, direction, or speed of objects. It can be used to detect\naircraft, ships, spacecraft, guided missiles, motor vehicles, weather\nformations, and terrain. The radar dish or antenna transmits pulses of radio\nwaves or microwaves which bounce off any object in their path. The object\nreturns a tiny part of the wave's energy to a dish or antenna which is usually\nlocated at the same site as the transmitter.\n\nRadar was secretly developed by several nations before and during World War II.\nThe term RADAR was coined in 1940 by the United States Navy as an acronym for\n'RA'dio'D'etection'A'nd'R'anging. {{cite web\n|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/radar |title= Radar definition in multiple\ndictionaries |publisher=Answers.com\n| date=\n|accessdate=2008-10-09}} The term radar has since entered English and\nother languages as the common noun radar, losing all capitalization.\n\nThe modern uses of radar are highly diverse, including air traffic control,\nradar astronomy, air-defense systems, antimissile systems; marine radars to\nlocate landmarks and other ships; aircraft anticollision systems; ocean\nsurveillance systems, outer space surveillance and rendezvous systems;\nmeteorological precipitation monitoring; altimetry and flight control systems;\nguided missile target locating systems; and ground-penetrating radar for\ngeological observations. High tech radar systems are associated with digital\nsignal processing and are capable of extracting useful information from very\nhigh noise levels.\n\nOther systems similar to radar make use of other parts of the electromagnetic\nspectrum. One example is \"lidar\", which uses visible light from lasers rather\nthan radio waves.\n","recorded":1362124147,"portal":[],"list":[],"links":"583","instances":["disambiguation","radio","radar_countermeasure","meteorology","radar","physics","geology","warfare","physics","raf","waves","navigation","electronics"],"pdf":["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/11/DE165546.pdf","http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e9/DE169154.pdf","http://www.mit.edu/~lrv/cornell/publications/Ground%20Surveillance%20Radars%20and%20Military%20Intelligence.pdf","http://www.mit.edu/~lrv/cornell/publications/Ground%20Surveillance%20Radars%20and%20Military%20Intelligence.pdf","http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA250517&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf","http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA250517&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf","http://www.cientificosaficionados.com/libros/CERN/vacio9-CERN.pdf","http://www.cientificosaficionados.com/libros/CERN/vacio9-CERN.pdf","http://www.xs4all.nl/~aobauer/Huelspart1def.pdf","http://math.la.asu.edu/~kuang/LM/030902-Radar_History10.pdf"],"categories":["Avionics","Aircraft instruments","Radar","Microwave technology","Measuring instruments","Navigational equipment","Air traffic control","Acronyms","Science and technology during World War II","Targeting (warfare)"],"headings":["History","Applications","Principles","Radar signal processing","Engineering","See also","Notes","References","Further reading","External links"],"tags":[["oboe","navigation"],["pathfinder","raf"],["precipitation","meteorology"],["crust","geology"],["reflection","physics"],["reflection","physics"],["chaff","radar_countermeasure"],["polarization","waves"],["coherence","physics"],["precipitation","meteorology"],["chaff","radar_countermeasure"],["polarization","waves"],["receiver","radio"],["coherence","physics"],["gallium(iii_arsenide"],["hohentwie